    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "### Description\n\nIt would be quite helpful if this repo's README.MD included a section on setting up a custom LSP server. I work at a company that has its own LSP server primarily for use with VSCode and forks. In order to get the LSP server to work in neovim without warnings, I had to do approximately the following:\n\n```lua\nlocal config = require(\"lspconfig.configs\")\nlocal custom_lsp_config = {\n  name = \"custom_lsp\",\n  cmd = \"/path/to/custom_lsp\",\n  filetypes = { \"custom_lsp_supported_filetype\" },\n  root_dir = { \"custom_lsp_root_dir\" },\n}\nconfigs.custom_lsp = { default_config = custom_lsp_config }\nvim.lsp.config[\"custom_lsp\"] = custom_lsp_config\nvim.lsp.enable(\"custom_lsp\")\n```\n\nWould a PR adding this to the README be welcome or is there another place this could be documented? Another possible place would be in `:help lsp-quickstart`",
    "closed_at": null,
    "closed_by": null,
    "comment_data": [
        {
            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "`require(\"lspconfig.configs\")` is deprecated and will be removed, as indicated in this repo's readme. it should not be used with `vim.lsp.config`.\n\nin Nvim 0.11+, `:help lsp-config` explains how to define a config. the summary is:\n\n1. define a file in `lsp/foo.lua` somewhere on your runtimepath \n2. that lua module must return the config\n    - there are 100s of examples in this repo in the lsp/ directory: https://github.com/neovim/nvim-lspconfig/tree/master/lsp\n\nmaybe we should make this a bit clearer.",
